      <hedline>
        <hl1>Pandora's Box of Prayers</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter by Barbara Bernstein of ACLU on appellate ruling reinstating Alabama decision that students may initiate prayer in classrooms or at school events; points out that atheists and agnostics may also demand time for statements, which would create kind of religious divisiveness that nation has avoided for more than 200 years (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>You report that a federal appeals court reinstated an Alabama decision allowing students to initiate and lead prayer in a classroom, assembly or football game as long as school officials do not force them to do so or participate in any way (news article, Oct. 21).</p>
        <p>Does this mean that atheists and agnostics may demand an equal chance in the same setting to make statements about their denials or doubts about religious faith? For that matter, if a student invokes Jesus, will a Jew, Muslim or Hindu be given equal time?</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>You report that a federal appeals court reinstated an Alabama decision allowing students to initiate and lead prayer in a classroom, assembly or football game as long as school officials do not force them to do so or participate in any way (news article, Oct. 21).</p>
        <p>Does this mean that atheists and agnostics may demand an equal chance in the same setting to make statements about their denials or doubts about religious faith? For that matter, if a student invokes Jesus, will a Jew, Muslim or Hindu be given equal time?</p>
        <p>Imagine the kind of religious divisiveness that this ruling will invite. This is precisely what our separation of church and state has avoided for more than 200 years, making us the most religiously free country in the world.</p>
        <p>BARBARA BERNSTEIN  Executive Director, Nassau Chapter  American Civil Liberties Union  Mineola, N.Y., Oct. 21, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
